The drug release experiments effectively demonstrate the characteristics of GPI and HANPs, as shown in Fig. S5. Fig. S5(a) reveals the pronounced acid-sensitive nature of GPI(DOX), attributable to the primary composition of GQDs in GPI. This is further explained by the hydrolysis of the NH2 groups to NH3
                        + in an acidic environment, leading to the release of doxorubicin from π-π stacking interactions [55]. On the other hand, the drug release curve for HANPs (Fig. S5(b)), modeled with doxorubicin, distinctly exhibits the advantageous pharmacokinetics imparted by HA, with sustained drug release up to the third day [56]. This gradual release undoubtedly provides a favorable basis for both in vitro and in vivo demonstrations. As described in the Experimental Methods section, we utilized in vitro cytotoxicity assays to assess the potential of HANPs(TAK)/GPI(DOX) as a therapeutic strategy and to determine the optimal anticancer drug for this system. Through a comprehensive assessment, we compared the viability of HCT116 cancer cells in each group after treatment with of HANPs loaded with various anticancer drugs, including SB-590885 (SB), TAK-632 (TAK), glutaminase inhibitor 968 (GI), curcumin (CU), and the HANPs/GPI (DOX) system, using the MTT assay (Fig. 6
                        ). The results suggested great cancer inhibition potential for all the treatments, and the cell viability further decreased when the cells were loaded with doxorubicin (DOX) (Fig. 6).
